    	cin &gt;&gt; DegreeOfCam;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Please Enter Amount of Lift : &quot;;
    	cin &gt;&gt; ValveLift;
    	
    	
    	double Pi = 3.141593; // Rounded version of Pi
    	double Rads = 0.017453; // This is equal to (Pi / 180)
    	double Product1;
    	
    	//Product1 = cosf((DegreesToRadians(DegreeOfCam / 2)));
    
    	Product1 = 0.999688; // This is the correct Product of the &quot;Cos((Pi/180)*(DegreeOfCam / 2))&quot;
    
    	double Radius1 = (-(2.0 * BaseRadius * FlankRadius) + ((BaseRadius + ValveLift)*(BaseRadius + ValveLift))
    		+ (BaseRadius * BaseRadius) + (2 * (BaseRadius + ValveLift) * (FlankRadius - BaseRadius) * Product1)); // This is the first radius for calculation of nose radius
    
    	double Radius2 = ((BaseRadius + ValveLift - FlankRadius) - ((BaseRadius - FlankRadius) * Product1)) * 2.0; // This is the second radius for calculation of nose radius
    
    	double NoseRadius = Radius1 / Radius2; // This is the main calculation for the nose radius
    
    	double WrongProduct = cos((Pi/180) * (DegreeOfCam / 2)); // This is the wrong calcuation for &quot;Cos((Pi/180)*(DegreeOfCam / 2))&quot;    WHY????????
    
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Product1 is : &quot; &lt;&lt; Product1 &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Radius 1 is : &quot; &lt;&lt; Radius1 &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Radius 2 is : &quot; &lt;&lt; Radius2 &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n\nThe Rads : &quot; &lt;&lt; Rads;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n\nPi : &quot; &lt;&lt; Pi;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n\nProduct 1 : &quot; &lt;&lt; Product1;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n\nThe Wrong Product is : &quot; &lt;&lt; WrongProduct;
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n\nThe nose radius is : &quot; &lt;&lt; NoseRadius;
    
    }

The reason this is so critical is that this particular function creates the basis for another function that creates a table of 360 dimensions and these dimensions need to be correct. I currently test my methods using a console before using them directly in my program.

answers.body_markdown:
For the current (2016/2019) version of Word on Mac (mine is v. 16.29 (19090802)), e.g. after 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-xsl --&gt;

             &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;b:Version&quot;&gt;
                &lt;xsl:text&gt;2019.9.29&lt;/xsl:text&gt;
             &lt;/xsl:when&gt;


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

you will need to insert code like this: 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-xsl --&gt;

             &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;b:OfficeStyleKey&quot;&gt;
                &lt;xsl:text&gt;David Teste&lt;/xsl:text&gt;
             &lt;/xsl:when&gt;


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

That test does not appear to have been required since around the 2010 version of Office on Windows. I am surprised it is still needed on Mac as the other main Mac-specific Bibliography feature (different footnote citations) appears to have been removed. It is possible that you have a more recent version of Mac Word than me where you do not need that code, but you also have copies of the 2011 version where it may still be needed.

NB in this version of Word the correct folder for these Bibliography Style .xsl files appears to be 

~/Library/Group Containers/UBF8T346G9.Office/User Content/Citations

(&quot;~&quot; means the top-level user folder, e.g. /Macintosh HD/Users/myusername)

