You have said that you need not worry about the looping of 30 days and thus you simply desire the flat number of days.

I am assuming you have also requested a number from the user as well as the release type.

Knowing this, we may write the following:

```
String releaseType;
int coDay;

// Insert your code to scan the users input.

if (releaseType == &quot;NEW&quot;) {
    coDay += 14;
} else {
    coDay += 21;
}

System.out.println(coDay);
```

`+=` means &quot;equivalent to itself, plus ...&quot;. So `coDay += 14` means `coDay = coDay + 14`, meaning that we are able to add 14 days to the users input, if it is `&quot;NEW&quot;`, and if not, add 21 instead.

You may use a java date, not something custom with ints, like `LocalDate`, and with a type you may add the good number of day :

    static LocalDate checkoutDate(LocalDate date, String type){
        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;NEW&quot;))
            return date.plusDays(14);
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;OLD&quot;))
            return date.plusDays(21);
        else 
            return date;
    }
    // without specific object but can&#39;t handle month problematic
    static int checkoutDate(int day, String type){
        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;NEW&quot;))
            return day + 14;
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;OLD&quot;))
            return day + 21;
        else 
            return day;
    }

Then set, or ask the user a date and a type and use it like

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        LocalDate date = LocalDate.now();
        System.out.println(checkoutDate(date, &quot;NEW&quot;)); // 2019-10-20
        System.out.println(checkoutDate(date, &quot;OLD&quot;)); // 2019-10-27
    }

